03952nam a22006015i 9780292767645DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212000txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927676457 a10.7560/7160492doi  a(DE-B1597)586597  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aQL737.C2bR66 2000 7aNAT0190002bisacsh04a599.7/09722211 ade la Rosa, Carlos L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Guide to the Carnivores of Central America :bNatural History, Ecology, and Conservation /cCarlos L. de la Rosa, Claudia C. Nocke. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2000  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tThe Order Carnivora in Central America -- tFamily Felidae: The Wild Cats -- tFamily Procyonidae: Coatis, Raccoons, and Relatives -- tFamily Mustelidae: Skunks, Grisons, Weasels, Otters, and Others -- tFamily Canidae: Dogs, Coyotes, and Foxes -- tThe Future of Central American Carnivores: Conservation Issues -- tA Few Final Words -- tGlossary -- tLiterature Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCarnivores such as pumas, jaguars, and ocelots have roamed the neotropical forests of Central America for millennia. Enshrined in the myths of the ancient Maya, they still inspire awe in the region's current inhabitants, as well as in the ecotourists and researchers who come to experience Central America's diverse and increasingly endangered natural environment. This book is one of the first field guides dedicated to the carnivores of Central America. It describes the four indigenous families—wild cats, raccoons and their relatives, skunks and their relatives, and wild canids—and their individual species that live in the region. The authors introduce each species by recounting a first-person encounter with it, followed by concise explanations of its taxonomy, scientific name, English and Spanish common names, habitat, natural history, and conservation status. Range maps show the animal's past and current distribution, while Claudia Nocke's black-and-white drawings portray it visually. The concluding chapter looks to the carnivores' future, including threats posed by habitat destruction and other human activities, and describes some current conservation programs. Designed for citizens of and visitors to Central America, as well as specialists, this book offers an excellent introduction to a group of fascinating, threatened, and still imperfectly understood animals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aCarnivorazCentral America. 0aCarnivora-Central America. 7aNATURE / Animals / Mammals.2bisacsh1 aNocke, Claudia C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292767645423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292767645/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK